The paper discusses the use of the sum-of-squares semidefinite programming hierarchy for solving planted problems, which are a type of problem in computer science that involves finding hidden structures in random noisy inputs. This topic is closely related to several sub-fields of computer science, including data structures (cs.DS), machine learning (cs.LG), information theory (cs.IT), computational complexity (cs.CC), and social and information networks (cs.SI). Given the broad scope of the paper and the fact that it touches on many different areas of computer science, it is likely to be relevant to researchers in all of these sub-fields.
